        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Spectral Setup:  We specify one 1.8 GHz band devoted to the continuum. to be observed with ~1.5 km/s spectral resolution.  These bands include the brightest 0.85 mm lines expected from an RSG envelope such as HCN, HCO+, CS, and CO   

Lines to be observed include:  12CO J=3-2, HCN J=4-3, HCO+ J=4-3, and CS J=7-6.  

A full bandwidth of ~8 GHz is needed to cover as many available molecular tracers as possible and to maximize continuum sensitivity.   </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To resolve the ring, an angular resolution of 1" is required.  At this resolution, ALMA has about 30 beams along the ring.   For 85 K dust concentrated the expected flux per beam is about 0.3 mJy.  Thus, a continuum sensitivity of 0.07 mJy in a 1" beam is required.

The corresponding spectral line sensitivity is about 30 mK.  At this sensitivity, CO will be detected with high signal-to noise for normal ISM abundance of 7e-5.  A 30 mK requirement enables a sensitive search.  

The ring outer diameter is around 7" to 10" and it is liekly that outside the ionization front there is a more extended envelope. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Infrared observations indicate a minimum gas mass (assuming gas-to-dust ratio of 100) of 0.5 to 1 Solar mass.   Extrapolating to 350 GHz, at D = 7 kpc, an envelope containing  1 Solar mass of  gas is expected to produce a total flux = 1.4  4 mJy for a dust temperature of 20 K.  Mid-IR observations show that the inner edge of the 5 radius ring has a dust temperature of  85 K.  If most of the gas is in a compact ring, or if the dispersed dust is this warm, the expect continuum flux from dust is  9  24 mJy.  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText> This program requires high continuum sensitivity provided by the the full use of the basebands.  However, we also need to retain the spectral resolution to enable the study of the kinematics on 1 km/s scales.  The Kepler (and escape speeds) at the radius of the ring are under 1 km/s for a 20 Solar mass star.  The gas is expected to be cold, with a local sound speed also under 1 km/s.  On arc-second scales, we expect narrow-line widths.  Additionally, other molecular species may inhabit the neutral envelope and we would like to retain the spectral resolution to characterize these.  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
