    <prp:abstract>SBW1 is a 50,000 Solar luminosity blue supergiant star located at a distance of 7 kpc behind the Carina Nebula.  It is surrounded by a remarkable set of three circumstellar rings;  a bright 5" radius ring and two  off-plane rings.  SBW1 is a virtual twin to SN 1987A and joins the handful of Galactic massive post-main sequence stars surrounded by equatorial rings.  It is the clearest example of a triple ring system surrounding a blue supergiant.

Band 7 ALMA observations are proposed to search for dust and molecular line emission and to determine the mass and geometry of the neutral circumstellar disk and envelope of this massive post-main-sequence star.  These observations will measure the dust mass, radial velocity structure, and relative chemical abundances in this remarkable object.  

The results will shed light on the shaping of bipolar nebulae, asymmetric and axisymmetric mass ejection processes, and the circumstellar environments into which supernovae explode.
A direct understanding of this environment will provide models for unresolved SNe like SN2009ip where there is active debate about the circumstellar geometry.</prp:abstract>
